      <div class="bridge-text">
        <div class="section-label">Industry to Academia</div>
        <h2 class="section-heading">Why Experience<br>Changes What<br>You Teach</h2>
        <p>Most engineering faculty follow a linear path from undergraduate through PhD into a faculty position. Dr. Tipton did not. He spent <strong>more than 25 years in industry</strong> before pursuing his doctorate, and that path is the most important thing he brings into the classroom.</p>
        <p>The result is a teacher who has seen good engineering fail in production, watched a poorly specified sensor destroy a product launch, and navigated the gap between what an equation predicts and what a machined part actually does. That context cannot be faked, and students know it.</p>

        <div class="bridge-callout">
          <p>Writing about this experience in <strong>Nature</strong> in 2022, Dr. Tipton described navigating a midlife PhD not as a career pivot, but as the natural completion of a curiosity that industry alone could not satisfy. That essay has been read by thousands of engineers and academics considering similar transitions.</p>
        </div>
      </div>

      <div>
